<Link id="l00046" /><CodeLine lineNumber="46"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00047" /><CodeLine lineNumber="47"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// This represents a single basic block in LLVM. A basic block is simply a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00048" /><CodeLine lineNumber="48"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// container of instructions that execute sequentially. Basic blocks are Values</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00049" /><CodeLine lineNumber="49"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// because they are referenced by instructions such as branches and switch</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00050" /><CodeLine lineNumber="50"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// tables. The type of a BasicBlock is &quot;Type::LabelTy&quot; because the basic block</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00051" /><CodeLine lineNumber="51"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// represents a label to which a branch can jump.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00052" /><CodeLine lineNumber="52"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00053" /><CodeLine lineNumber="53"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// A well formed basic block is formed of a list of non-terminating</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00054" /><CodeLine lineNumber="54"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// instructions followed by a single terminator instruction. Terminator</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// instructions may not occur in the middle of basic blocks, and must terminate</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the blocks. The BasicBlock class allows malformed basic blocks to occur</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00057" /><CodeLine lineNumber="57"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// because it may be useful in the intermediate stage of constructing or</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00058" /><CodeLine lineNumber="58"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// modifying a program. However, the verifier will ensure that basic blocks are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00059" /><CodeLine lineNumber="59"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// &quot;well formed&quot;.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00728" /><CodeLine lineNumber="728"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Asserts that instruction order numbers are marked invalid, or that they</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00729" /><CodeLine lineNumber="729"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// are in ascending order. This is constant time if the ordering is invalid,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00730" /><CodeLine lineNumber="730"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// and linear in the number of instructions if the ordering is valid. Callers</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00731" /><CodeLine lineNumber="731"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// should be careful not to call this in ways that make common operations</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00732" /><CodeLine lineNumber="732"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// O(n^2). For example, it takes O(n) time to assign order numbers to</span></CodeLine>
